IOTA Interoperability for the DOT 
============================================================

This document specifies how the IOTA layer interoperates with
the Dot Operator (⊙) without redefining its identity. DOT is a
constitutional operator governing the admissibility of
representational transitions between states, frameworks and
claims. DOT is NOT a Data Object and must NOT be imported as
one.

IOTA therefore provides an operator‑level bridge that allows
external operators (such as ⊙) to be invoked within a GAF‑
governed ecosystem while preserving their identity, role and
representational function.

------------------------------------------------------------
A1. IDENTITY OF THE DOT OPERATOR
------------------------------------------------------------

DOT = ⊙

Role:
    • Constitutional operator
    • Governs admissibility of representational transitions
    • Acts on states, frameworks, claims
    • NOT an object, NOT a token, NOT a subtype

DOT must remain:
    • external,
    • operator‑level,
    • non‑collapsing,
    • non‑substitutable.

------------------------------------------------------------
A2. IOTA OPERATOR‑LEVEL INTEROPERABILITY
------------------------------------------------------------

IOTA does NOT import DOT.
IOTA does NOT tokenize DOT.
IOTA does NOT convert DOT into TERMS objects.

Instead, IOTA provides:

    OperatorBridge(⊙) = {
        InvocationRules,
        ContextualBinding,
        TransitionInterface,
        AdmissibilityRelay,
        ProvenanceReference
    }

This bridge allows GAF‑governed systems to invoke DOT
without redefining DOT’s constitutional role.

------------------------------------------------------------
A3. INVOCATION RULES
------------------------------------------------------------

DOT may be invoked only through operator‑level calls:

    Invoke(⊙, State_i, State_j)

Where:
    State_i, State_j ∈ RepresentationalStates
    ⊙ determines admissibility of the transition.

IOTA ensures:
    • DOT is invoked, not imported
    • DOT governs transitions, not objects
    • DOT’s output is represented in TERMS without altering DOT

------------------------------------------------------------
A4. TRANSITION INTERFACE
------------------------------------------------------------

IOTA provides a neutral interface:

    TransitionInterface(⊙) = {
        InputState      = S_i,
        OutputState     = S_j,
        DOT_Admissible  = ⊙(S_i → S_j),
        Representation  = TERMS encoding of S_j,
        Justification   = JOT‑TERMS justification,
        Placement       = SPOT‑TERMS placement
    }

DOT governs the admissibility.
TERMS governs the representation.
GAF governs the justification.
SPOT governs the placement.

No identity collapse occurs.

------------------------------------------------------------
A5. ADMISSIBILITY RELAY
------------------------------------------------------------

DOT’s admissibility decision is relayed into GAF:

    If ⊙(S_i → S_j) = admissible:
        GAF_Admissibility := true
    Else:
        GAF_Admissibility := false

GAF does NOT override DOT.
GAF records DOT’s decision as an external admissibility source.

------------------------------------------------------------
A6. PROVENANCE REFERENCE
------------------------------------------------------------

IOTA preserves DOT provenance:

    Provenance(⊙) = {
        OperatorIdentity,
        InvocationContext,
        TransitionRecord,
        ExternalReference
    }

DOT’s identity remains external and operator‑level.

------------------------------------------------------------
A7. FORMAL DEFINITION
------------------------------------------------------------

IOTA(⊙) = (
    OperatorBridge(⊙),
    InvocationRules,
    TransitionInterface,
    AdmissibilityRelay,
    ProvenanceReference
)

Where:
    ⊙ remains a constitutional operator
    IOTA provides interoperability
    GAF governs invocation context
    TERMS represents resulting states
    JOT/SPOT govern justification and placement

------------------------------------------------------------
A8. OPERATOR BRIDGE
------------------------------------------------------------
IOTA Operator‑Bridge
Interoperability Layer for External Operators 

The IOTA Operator‑Bridge provides a neutral, non‑collapsing
interoperability layer that allows external constitutional 
operators to be invoked inside a GAF‑governed ecosystem 
without being imported, redefined, or converted into TERMS
objects.

This specification ensures:
     External Operators remains an operator
     Operators admissibility decisions remain authoritative
      externally
     TERMS only encodes resulting representational states
     GAF governs invocation context, not external Operators
     IOTA provides the bridge, not reinterpretation

TERMS retains full internal decisional authority. External 
operators (including ⊙) may be invoked by users of the 
TERMS ecosystem, but they do not govern TERMS, do not 
impose admissibility, and do not determine successor‑state 
logic. Their admissibility decisions remain external, 
optional, and non‑binding.

IOTA provides a bridge for possible invocation, not a
dependency.

GAF governs the context of invocation, not the operator
itself.

TERMS governs representation, justification, placement,
and decisional logic.

External operators remain external. TERMS remains sovereign.

Summary

     The IOTA Operator‑Bridge:
     preserves DOT as a constitutional operator (⊙)
     prevents category collapse
     maintains operator identity
     enables admissible invocation
     records provenance
     represents only the results of DOT transitions

------------------------------------------------------------
A9. BRIDGE SPECIFICATION
------------------------------------------------------------
Operator Identity Preservation

External Operator Definition
---
An external operator O_ext is any constitutional operator 
originating outside the TERMS ecosystem.

DOT is treated as:

     O_ext = ⊙

Identity Constraints
---
     O_ext must not be tokenized
     O_ext must not be imported
     O_ext must not be represented as a Data Object
     O_ext must not be collapsed into TERMS ontology
     O_ext must remain external and operator‑level

Operator‑Bridge Architecture
---
The Operator‑Bridge is a five‑component interoperability 
structure:

OperatorBridge(O_ext) = {

    InvocationRules,
    ContextualBinding,
    TransitionInterface,
    AdmissibilityRelay,
    ProvenanceReference

}

Invocation Rules
---
Invocation Form

External operators are invoked through IOTA:

     Invoke(O_ext, S_i, S_j)

Where:

     S_i = initial representational state
     S_j = candidate successor state
     O_ext determines admissibility of the transition

Invocation Constraints
---
Invocation must be explicit
Invocation must preserve operator identity
Invocation must not reinterpret operator semantics
Invocation must not imply containment or equivalence

Contextual Binding
---
IOTA binds external operator invocation to GAF‑governed 
context:

ContextualBinding(O_ext) = {

    InvocationDomain,
    OperationalConstraints,
    Residuals,
    FailureConditions

}

InvocationDomain
Defines the operational domain in which O_ext is admissibly
invoked

Residuals
Residual structures from O_ext must be preserved and 
declared

Failure Conditions
Failure conditions must be explicit

Transition Interface
---
The Transition Interface converts operator‑level
admissibility into TERMS‑level representational structure 
without redefining the operator.

TransitionInterface(O_ext) = {
    InputState      = S_i,
    OutputState     = S_j,
    Admissible      = O_ext(S_i → S_j),
    Representation  = TERMS(S_j),
    Justification   = JOT(S_j),
    Placement       = SPOT(S_j)
}

Operator governs admissibility
O_ext determines whether the transition is admissible.

TERMS governs representation
TERMS encodes the resulting state S_j.

GAF governs justification context
GAF records admissibility but does not override O_ext.

SPOT governs placement
---
SPOT assigns representational placement.

Admissibility Relay
DOT’s admissibility decision is relayed into GAF:

If O_ext(S_i → S_j) = admissible:
    GAF.Admissibility := true
Else:
    GAF.Admissibility := false

Relay Constraints
---
GAF records DOT’s decision
GAF governs the context of invocation

Provenance Reference
---
IOTA preserves operator provenance:

Provenance(O_ext) = {
    OperatorIdentity,
    InvocationContext,
    TransitionRecord,
    ExternalReference
}

Formal Definition
---
The complete operator‑bridge is:

IOTA(O_ext) = (
    OperatorBridge(O_ext),
    InvocationRules,
    TransitionInterface,
    AdmissibilityRelay,
    ProvenanceReference
)

Where:
     O_ext remains external
     IOTA provides interoperability
     GAF governs invocation context
     TERMS represents resulting states
     JOT/SPOT govern justification and placement

