A11. ROLE OF DOT IN THE ECOSYSTEM
------------------------------------------------------------

DOT remains:

    • an external constitutional operator,
    • governing admissibility of transitions,
    • invoked through IOTA,
    • referenced by GAF,
    • represented in TERMS only through its outputs.

DOT can be chosen to governs transitions; TERMS governs
representation.

------------------------------------------------------------
A12. BOUNDARY CONDITIONS FOR EXTERNAL OPERATORS
------------------------------------------------------------

OperatorImportBoundary
---
The following conditions ensure that external operators remain
external and are never treated as a Data Object or TERMS-
native construct.

Hard Prohibitions
---
    • No tokenization:
        ⊙ must not be converted into (⧈, ⧉) TERMS tokens.
    • No Σ_IOTA construction:
        ⊙ must not appear as an entry in Σ_IOTA.
    • No JOT/SPOT generation:
        ⊙ must not be represented as a JOT-TERMS object
        or SPOT-TERMS placement.
    • No representational embedding:
        ⊙ must not be serialized into TERMS objects or
        embedded in representational notation.
    • No operator-to-object coercion:
        ⊙ must not be treated as a Data Object, subtype,
        or governed actor under GAF.

Semantic Opaqueness
---
    • No partial evaluation of ⊙ inside IOTA.
    • No prediction or approximation of ⊙ admissibility
      by GAF or TERMS.
    • No caching or memoization of ⊙ decisions as if they
      were local rules.
    • No substitution of ⊙ with local admissibility
      heuristics.

Boundary Condition Summary
---
DOT remains:
    • external,
    • operator-level,
    • non-collapsing,
    • non-substitutable.

Any violation of these boundary conditions constitutes a
collapse of operator identity and triggers failure handling
under IOTA.

------------------------------------------------------------
A13. ADMISSIBILITY HIERARCHY (DOT, GAF, TERMS)
------------------------------------------------------------

AdmissibilityHierarchy = {
    DOT_Admissibility,
    GAF_Admissibility,
    TERMS_Admissibility
}

1. DOT_Admissibility (External Constitutional Layer)
---
    • DOT evaluates transitions:
        ⊙(S_i → S_j) ∈ {admissible, inadmissible}.
    • DOT’s decision is authoritative for its own domain.
    • DOT’s decision is relayed but not reinterpreted:

        If ⊙(S_i → S_j) = admissible:
            GAF_Admissibility := true
        Else:
            GAF_Admissibility := false

2. GAF_Admissibility (Governance Context Layer)
---
    • GAF governs the context of invocation, not DOT itself.
    • GAF may:
        – permit or block invocation of ⊙,
        – record DOT’s decision as an external source,
        – apply additional contextual constraints.
    • GAF may NOT:
        – override DOT’s admissibility decision,
        – reinterpret DOT’s semantics,
        – substitute DOT with local rules.

3. TERMS_Admissibility (Internal Logic Layer)
---
    • TERMS governs successor-state logic and internal
      representational admissibility.
    • TERMS may:
        – accept or reject S_j as a valid successor state,
        – apply internal consistency and moderation rules.
    • TERMS may NOT:
        – claim to govern DOT,
        – treat DOT’s decision as binding on internal logic.

Hierarchy Summary
---
    • DOT governs operator-level admissibility.
    • GAF governs invocation context and records DOT.
    • TERMS governs internal representation and successor
      state logic.

Conflicts are resolved by:
    • DOT remaining authoritative for its own domain,
    • GAF controlling whether invocation occurs,
    • TERMS controlling whether S_j is adopted internally.

